<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-01-07T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-01-07T15:00:00-05:00" n="64" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d64">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">851G.00/1–417: Circular telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of state</gloss> to
                                certain <gloss type="to">Diplomatic Officers</gloss>
                            </hi><note n="16" xml:id="d64fn16">At Paris.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-01-07T15:00:00-05:00">January 7,
                                    1947—3 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Nav Attaché Bangkok<note n="17" xml:id="d64fn17">Comdr. Alfred W. Gardes,
                                Jr.</note> reports French now trying clear lines Saigon to Cambodian
                            border using all French Indochina reserves. These troops and 16,000 now
                            en route from France then be thrown into all out reconquest Tonkin where
                            puppet Govt may be set up. This is plan of d’Argenlieu and LeClerc,<note n="18" xml:id="d64fn18">Maj. Gen. Jacques-Philippe Leclerc,
                                Inspector General of French Armies in North Africa, formerly
                                Commander in Chief of French Forces in the Far East.</note> with
                            Moutet wavering as leftists Saigou reportedly favor reopening
                            negotiations with Ho. Final decision be made when Moutet returns Paris
                            Jan 16.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>